revision.text:
The '''Al-Sweady Inquiry''' was a five-year [[public inquiry]] led by [[Thayne Forbes]] which investigated accusations of mistreatment of prisoners by the British Army following the [[Battle of Danny Boy]]. The enquiry commenced its investigations in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-30515369|title=Al-Sweady Inquiry: UK army murder claims 'deliberate lies'|date=17 December 2014|accessdate=17 December 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>
The inquiry cost nearly £25 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inquiry Expenditure and Costs|url=http://www.alsweadyinquiry.org/costs/index.htm|website=Al-Sweady Public Inquiry|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> The report was published in December 2014 and concluded that the allegations of torture and murder were "wholly without foundation and entirely the product of deliberate lies, reckless speculation and ingrained hostility",<ref name="GOV - Publication of the Al-Sweady inquiry report">{{cite web|title=Publication of the Al-Sweady inquiry report|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/publication-of-the-al-sweady-inquiry-report|website=News|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=15 February 2015|date=17 December 2014}}</ref> but that nine Iraqi detainees had been ill-treated.<ref name="Mistreatment but not murder">{{cite web|title=Al-Sweady inquiry: Iraqis mistreated but UK troops did not murder insurgents|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/dec/17/al-sweady-inquiry-uk-troops-mistreated-iraqi-prisoners-not-murder|accessdate=5 August 2016|date=17 December 2014}}</ref>
Subsequently Leigh Day, one of the law firms involved, were referred to the Solicitors Disciplinary Tribunal<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jan/05/law-firm-leigh-day-solicitors-disciplinary-tribunal-al-sweady-inquiry Law firm referred to disciplinary tribunal over Al-Sweady inquiry ]</ref> to answer complaints about its handling of action brought by Iraqi detainees against the Ministry of Defence. Another, Public Interest Lawyers, later closed down.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/aug/15/public-interest-lawyers-iraq-war-al-sweady-theresa-may-uk-troops Law firm at centre of Al-Sweady inquiry to close down, say reports]</ref>
