{{See also|Speed limits in the United States (rail)|Speed limits in the United States by jurisdiction|Road signs in the United States}}
<!-- NOTE: Do not split this article without discussion, see [[Talk:Speed limits in the United States/Archives/2008/December#The inevitable?]]. -->
{{Main|Speed limit|Speed limits by country}}
[[File:US Speed Limits May 2015.svg|thumb|upright=1.35|Map of speed limits in US states or counties]]
'''Speed limits in the United States''' are set by each state or [[Territories of the United States|territory.]] States also allowed [[County (United States)|counties]] and [[Municipality|municipalities]], to enact typically lower limits. Highway speed limits can range from an urban low of {{convert|25|mph|abbr=on|0}} to a rural high of {{convert|85|mph|abbr=on|0}}. Speed limits are typically posted in increments of {{convert|5|mph|0|spell=in}}. Some states have lower limits for [[#Truck speed limits|trucks]] and at [[#Night speed limits|night]], and occasionally there are [[#Minimum speed limits|minimum speed limits]]. 

The highest speed limits are generally {{convert|70|mph|abbr=on|0}} on the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] and the inland [[Eastern United States|eastern states]], {{convert|75|-|80|mph|kph|abbr=on}} in inland western states, along with Arkansas and Louisiana, and {{convert|65-70|mph|abbr=on|0}} on the [[East Coast of the United States|Eastern Seaboard]]. Alaska, Connecticut, Delaware, Massachusetts, New Jersey, New York, Puerto Rico, Rhode Island, and Vermont have a maximum limit of {{convert|65|mph|abbr=on|0}}, and Hawaii has a maximum limit of {{convert|60|mph|abbr=on|0}}. The [[District of Columbia]] and the [[U.S. Virgin Islands]] have a maximum speed limit of {{convert|55|mph|abbr=on}}. [[Guam]], the [[Northern Mariana Islands]] and [[American Samoa]] have speed limits of {{convert|45|mph|abbr=on}}. Two territories in the [[U.S. Minor Outlying Islands]] have their own speed limits: {{convert|40|mph|abbr=on}} in [[Wake Island]], and {{convert|15|mph|abbr=on}} in [[Midway Atoll]].<ref name="Wake"/><ref name="Midway">[https://www.govregs.com/regulations/expand/title50_chapterI_part38_subpartC_section38.13 Midway Atoll Code]</ref> Unusual for any state east of the Mississippi River, much of I-95 in Maine north of [[Bangor, Maine|Bangor]] allows up to {{convert|75|mph|abbr=on}}, and the same is true for up to 600 miles of freeways in [[Michigan]]. Portions of the Idaho, Montana, Nevada, South Dakota, Texas, Utah, and Wyoming road networks have {{convert|80|mph|abbr=on|0}} posted limits. The highest posted speed limit in the country is {{convert|85|mph|abbr=on}} and can be found only on the [[Texas State Highway 130]].

For 13 years (January 1974<ref>{{cite news |title= Nixon Approves Limit of 55 MPH |url= http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40610FD3F58137B93C1A9178AD85F408785F9&scp=1&sq=nixon%20approves%20limit%20of%2055&st=cse |accessdate=July 22, 2008 |work= The New York Times |pages= 1, 24 |date= January 3, 1974}} {{subscription required}}</ref>–April 1987<ref name="second">{{cite news |title= 55-m.p.h. Signs Sprout Out West, but New York Region Holds Off |url= https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/04/us/55-mph-signs-sprout-out-west-but-new-york-region-holds-off.html |accessdate=21 August 2016 |first=William G. |last=Blair |work= The New York Times |date= 4 April 1987}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/100th-congress/house-bill/2 |title=H.R.2 – 100th Congress (1987–1988): Surface Transportation and Uniform Relocation Assistance Act of 1987 |date=2 April 1987 |website=Congress.gov |publisher=Library of Congress |access-date=21 August 2016 }}</ref>), [[#Federal speed controls|federal law]] withheld [[Highway Trust Fund|Federal highway trust funds]] to states that had speed limits above {{convert|55|mph|kph|abbr=on}}.<ref name="second" /> From April 1987 to December 8, 1995, an amended federal law disincentivized speed limits above {{convert|65|mph|kph|abbr=on}}.

{{multiple image|direction=vertical|width=120|image1=Speed limit 80 sign.svg|image2=Night speed 65 sign.svg|image3=Trucks speed 55 sign.svg|footer=A standard sign indicating a speed limit of {{cvt|80|mph}}, a night-time speed limit of {{cvt|65|mph}}, and a truck speed limit of {{cvt|55|mph}} }}
[[File:SchoolZone-SpeedLimitSignAndLight.JPG|thumb|Speed limit sign at a school zone with a warning light]]

==Overview==
===Speed limits===
This table contains the most usual posted daytime speed limits, in [[miles per hour]], on typical roads in each category. The values shown are not necessarily the fastest or slowest. They usually indicate, but not always, [[statutory law|statutory]] speed limits. Some states and territories have lower [[#Truck speed limits|truck speed limits]] applicable to [[Semi-trailer truck|heavy trucks]]. If present, they are usually only on freeways or other high-speed roadways. Washington allows for speeds up to {{cvt|75|mph}}, but the highest posted signs are {{cvt|70|mph}}. Mississippi allows speeds up to {{cvt|80|mph|0}} on toll roads, but no such roads exist. Oklahoma removed the maximum speed of 75 from its laws, though no road has been posted higher than 75.

